<header>

	<h1>The Navigation Workshop</h1>

	<p>
		During this workshop you have to design navigation - both horizontal and vertical. With cool hover effects (except for mobile navigation of course). The workshop runs like this:	
	</p>
	<ol>
		<li>Form groups of 3 - 4 students</li>
		<li>Make a webpage hierarchy for a webpage with at least as many subpages as there are members in the group.</li>
		<li>Agree on a basic stylesheet.</li>
		<li>Let there be at least one breakpoint - so that your webpage will have one design on smaller screens and another design on say laptops.</li>
		<li>Design navigation options - horisontal and vertical menus with cool hover color effects</li>
		<li>Design navigation by well chosen icons</li>
		<li>Make navigation by text</li>
		<li>Add a site map (yep this could be one of the sub pages).</li>
		<li>Add a design manual in HTML5 / CSS (tip: @media print - again yeah this could be one of your sub pages)</li>	
		<li>Of course your navigation bar <em>must be present at all your webpages</em> ;-)</li>	
	</ol>
	
	<p>
		Use icons, images and and custom backgrounds in your designs.	
	</p>
	<p>
		Hand in your work at 13:45 as a group on Fronter. Then present your work to the class.	
	</p>
	<p>
		More info found in your book - see the chapter on formatting lists and on how to mark navigation.	
	</p>
	


</header>


